      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the abrupt and confusing goblin metaphor in my previous response! I clearly got carried away with the \"goblin stash of gold\" analogy and lost track of the actual legal explanation.\n\nTo answer your question clearly and directly:\n\nA **regular (non-durable) power of attorney** only gives you the authority to make decisions while your dad is mentally competent. If he becomes incapacitated (for example, due to dementia or a stroke), that document immediately stops working, and you cannot act on his behalf without going to court.\n\nA **durable power of attorney** includes a specific clause stating that your authority remains in effect even if your dad becomes incapacitated. This ensures that you can continue to manage his finances, pay bills, or handle property matters without needing to hire a lawyer or a court-appointed guardian.\n\nIn short: a regular one expires if he gets sick, while a durable one stays active so you can keep helping him even when he can't make decisions himself.",
